  "projectSchedule": [],
  "body": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Why you need a kit before you need it"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Emergencies happen at night, on bank holidays, and in bad weather. Your vet may be 40 minutes away. Having the right equipment to hand can mean the difference between a quick recovery and a dead animal. Build your kit before your first animal arrives."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Temperature and basic monitoring"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "A digital rectal thermometer is the single most useful item in any livestock kit. Normal temperature ranges vary by species:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Sheep and goats: 38.5 to 39.5 degrees C"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Cattle: 38.0 to 39.0 degrees C"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Pigs: 38.5 to 39.5 degrees C"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Always take temperature before calling the vet. It is the first thing they will ask. Write it down with the time."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Lubrication and delivery aids"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Keep a large bottle of veterinary lubricant gel. This is used when assisting with difficult deliveries in sheep, goats, and cattle. It reduces trauma to both dam and offspring. Do not attempt to assist a birth without it."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "A "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                "attrs": {
                  "termSlug": "stomach-tube"
                }
              }
            ],
            "text": "stomach tube"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " and syringe is important for newborn care. A lamb or kid that cannot suck needs fluids quickly. Ask your vet to show you how to pass the tube correctly before you need it in an emergency. An incorrectly placed tube going into the lungs instead of the stomach can be fatal."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "A "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                "attrs": {
                  "termSlug": "drenching-gun"
                }
              }
            ],
            "text": "drenching gun"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " allows you to give oral fluids, electrolytes, or wormer to adult animals that are reluctant to drink. Keep one suitable for your main species. Use separately for each animal if disease is suspected."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Wound care and antiseptic"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Keep "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                "attrs": {
                  "termSlug": "iodine-solution"
                }
              }
            ],
            "text": "iodine solution"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " in two strengths. A 0.5 percent dilute solution is used to dip or spray navel cords in newborns. Do this within 30 minutes of birth. Strong iodine (10 percent) is used to disinfect equipment."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Also keep:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Wound spray or antiseptic powder for cuts and grazes"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Cotton wool and gauze pads for cleaning wounds"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Conforming and self-adhesive bandage rolls"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Surgical tape"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Disposable gloves in a range of sizes"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Sterile scissors and curved forceps"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Colostrum supply"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Keep an emergency "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                "attrs": {
                  "termSlug": "colostrum"
                }
              }
            ],
            "text": "colostrum"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " supply for newborns. The easiest approach is to freeze excess colostrum from animals on your holding after each birth season. Label it with species and date. Use within 12 months. Thaw at room temperature or in warm water, never in a microwave."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "If you have no frozen stock, a powdered commercial colostrum substitute is a reasonable backup. It is not as effective as the real thing but is better than nothing. Keep one or two sachets in the kit at all times."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Additional items worth keeping"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Electrolyte sachets for scouring lambs or kids"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Lamb resuscitator (rubber bulb for clearing mucus from airways)"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Headtorch (lambing often happens at night)"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Penknife with a clean blade"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Notepad and pen for recording observations and times"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Your vet's number, the out-of-hours number, and the APHA helpline number on a card inside the lid"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Medicines and prescription items"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Many useful medicines require a vet prescription. Establish a relationship with a farm vet before you need one urgently. A vet who knows your holding can issue a written prescription for commonly used products. You can then source these through a licensed veterinary pharmacy and keep them on hand."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Store all medicines according to label instructions. Many require refrigeration. Check expiry dates at the start of each season. Dispose of expired medicines at a pharmacy or licensed waste point. Do not pour them down drains."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Maintaining the kit"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Check and restock the kit at the start of lambing season, before any calving period, and at least once in the summer. Note what you used and replace it within a week. A kit with gaps when you need it is worse than finding a gap before you do."
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  }
}